(Correction
    "Names do not carry their full ancestry. Enclosing crate, channel, module, type, and field context already supply meaning, so child names should not repeat every ancestor noun. Inside Spirit, intent is the domain; inside Entry, fields are already entry fields."
    "Do you understand how to name things now? Can you give me a breakdown of all your data types? Just get all your data types out of the contracts and let me see them. I want to see what you're doing and let me see if you understand how you need to name things properly. If you understand context, like as in these data types are in the context of being in this repository, this crate, right? This rest crate. They don't need to be like named all the way to the fucking sky. We understand they're from the signal spirit persona. So like the context tells us enough. This is about intent. And what's more is that once there is a basic containing type, let's say intent, there's an intent. Well, all the fields in that struct don't need to say that they're intent. They're fields in the intent struct. Like, you don't rename everything as things get encapsulated. They are implicitly of that encapsulation. They don't need to be renamed after all of their ancestors. You know, if I held the name of all my ancestors, I would be speaking until I die before I could spell my name out."
    "Generalizing the persona-spirit naming correction into the cross-workspace naming rule. Repeated intent wording is intentionally logged again rather than deduplicated because repeated phrasing reinforces the intent and preserves distinct verbatim evidence."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T15:46:23Z)

(Decision
    "Strengthen the no-abbreviations stance across all coding-related guidance files. The current exception list in skills/naming.md is too liberal — psyche pushed back: identifier is always better than id, and CPU is borderline (allowed only because it has become English). Default to spelling out; reach for the acronym exception sparingly. Most code-side shortenings (ctx, cfg, addr, db, tok, buf, ui) are convenience abbreviations, not English words; they belong in the offender table, not the exception list."
    "we don't allow abbreviations for almost anything except maybe ID, but even then identifier is actually better. So I don't, I wouldn't even say we allow ID. Maybe CPU. Okay. Like maybe, but only because it's become sort of part of the English language."
    "Tightening the abbreviation rule beyond what skills/naming.md currently encodes. Psyche's mood is 'almost nothing'; the wider acronym list of 13 items is too generous. Apply by removing id from the exception list, adding a leading caution that most short forms don't qualify, and reaffirming the spelled form is the default."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:20:00Z)

(Decision
    "Both load-bearing naming rules — full-English-words AND no-redundant-ancestor-context — must land in every coding-related guidance file with comparable emphasis, so agents pick up both together as a pair. The two rules pull in opposite directions; they only work together. ESSENCE.md needs a Naming section (AGENTS.md already references one as §'Naming' but the section does not exist). The redundant-ancestor rule, recently generalised from the persona-spirit Entry-not-IntentEntry correction, should be paired with the no-abbreviations rule everywhere."
    "let's make this clear in all the guidance files that are concerned"
    "Manifestation directive: bring the two naming rules together across coding skills. ESSENCE.md §Naming is the missing keystone (AGENTS.md's hard override references it as if it exists). skills/naming.md already carries both rules but with the abbreviation exception list too wide; skills/contract-repo.md and skills/rust-discipline.md carry partial coverage. All need the paired emphasis."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:20:00Z)

(Decision
    "Acronyms that have fully passed into general English are allowed in code: CPU, URL, HTTP, JSON. The test is whether the acronym has functionally become the English word — where the spelled form is awkward or no longer remembered. JSON specifically: 'no one even knows what JSON actually extends to.' Other technical acronyms (UUID, TCP, UDP, DNS) often qualify under the same test. Internal short forms (ctx, cfg, addr, db, os, ui, io, ram) are convenience shortenings, not English words — spell them. id explicitly does not qualify; use identifier."
    "Yeah, we can use URL, HTTP, JSON. … Yeah, we can use CPU definitely, and HTTP and JSON. JSON is not really an acronym. I mean, it is an acronym, but it's not an abbreviation. It's an acronym that has basically become, no one even knows what JSON actually extends to."
    "Settling the acronym exception list for skills/naming.md exception #4. Psyche affirmed CPU/URL/HTTP/JSON explicitly with the 'has it become the English word' test."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:35:00Z)

(Principle
  "Repeated prefixes or suffixes in sibling type names indicate a missing schema separation."
  "Recent repositories query. Changed file query. Comment message query. Why aren't these all queries with different payloads? Like query and then recent repositories. So query is the variant and it has another inner variant which is recent repositories. … when data types show up a pattern in the names where the same prefix or suffix keeps popping up, that is probably a sign that there is a logic separation that is being stuffed inside the names of the data types instead of coming out as a separate schema separation. More separation is better."
  "Psyche reacted to repository-ledger names such as RecentRepositoriesQuery, ChangedFileQuery, and CommitMessageQuery after the first redundant Repository-prefix rename pass. The concern is not just redundant namespace ancestry but repeated category words hiding a missing relation layer."
  Medium
  2026-05-19T16:34:02Z)

(Decision
    "The vocabulary 'signal types' refers to the types defined in signal-<component> contract crates — the Rust types that cross the wire as the typed schema of one signaling fabric. The psyche has named this surface explicitly so future conversations have a single term for it. Signal types include the per-relation request/reply/event variants, the typed records they wrap, and the typed identifiers/enums those records reference."
    "we're going to create our own language. So the signal types are obviously the biggest culprit."
    "Vocabulary lock-in: 'signal types' = the types defined in signal-* contract crates. Psyche introduced because they were 'tired of reaching for vocabulary.' Use this term in future conversations and guidance about contract-crate naming."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:50:00Z)

(Principle
    "Agents over-declarate signal type names — every type gets a fully descriptive name even when the surrounding namespace already supplies the context. This is wrong on multiple levels: (1) it stuffs logic into the name instead of into the schema, (2) it produces wrong separation of concerns (logic that should live in nested types ends up flat at the top), (3) it produces wrong schema shape (flat tables of names instead of trees that reflect the conceptual planes). The naming failure and the schema-shape failure are the same failure: not recognizing where logical planes diverge."
    "agents seem to want to create these fully declarative names on every single one of them. And that's just wrong from many points of view. It sort of stuffs logic. They end up not creating the right separation of concern, and they end up creating the wrong schema structure."
    "Diagnosing the over-declarative-name pattern: the symptom is repetitive prefixes; the cause is the agent failing to recognize logical planes and forcing everything flat."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:50:00Z)

(Principle
    "Signal-type schemas should grow into trees, not stay flat. When the schema needs a new logic plane (e.g. a query plane), that plane gets its own sub-structure — a nested set of types under one conceptual root — not a sequence of flat top-level variants each carrying the plane's name as a suffix. Example: 'RecentFileQuery, RecentRepositoryQuery, FileChangedQuery' as flat top-level types is the wrong shape; the right shape is a Query subtree with its own structure where each query kind reflects its variant in the tree position, not in the name."
    "the schema needs to grow more complex. That's what is happening, and then the agent doesn't see how the schema needs to evolve because it doesn't create the base schema properly from the beginning. So it ends up being this really stuffy, flat table of things where it should really grow into a tree."
    "Naming the underlying schema-shape failure: agents create flat top-level variant sets where the schema should branch into sub-trees representing conceptual planes (read vs write, query vs assertion, lifecycle stage, etc.)."
    Maximum
    2026-05-19T18:50:00Z)

